<div class="container-xl py-5">
    <h1 class="mb-3">Anxiety</h1>
    <p style="text-align: ;">Anxiety is a natural human feeling experienced by many children when facing problems, before tests, or making important decisions. However, anxiety disorders vary and can interfere with a child's ability to lead a normal life. Anxiety disorder is a significant psychological condition where individuals respond to specific things or situations with fear and apprehension, exhibiting physical signs of anxiety (such as increased heart rate and sweating).</p>
</div>
    <div class="container-xl py-5">
        <h2 class="mb-3"> Causes</h2>
        <p style="text-align: left;">Children can pick up anxiety behaviors from anxious individuals around them or develop anxiety after stressful events like:</p>
        <p style="text-align: left;">- frequent changes in home or school.</p>
        <p style="text-align: left;">- parental conflicts in the child's presence.</p>
        <p style="text-align: left;">- serious illness, or accidents.</p>
        <p style="text-align: left;">- the death of a close relative or friend.</p>
        <p style="text-align: left;">- Children with ADHD or autism spectrum disorders are more prone to anxiety problems.</p>
      </div>
    <div class="container-xl py-5">
       <h2 class="mb-3">Symptoms</h2>
       <p style="text-align: left;">When a child feels anxious, he may be unable to express it in some cases. It may be noted that the child is:</p>
       <p style="text-align: left;">- irritable or crying.</p>
       <p style="text-align: left;">- He has difficulty sleeping.</p>
       <p style="text-align: left;">- He wakes up at night. He has bad dreams.</p>
       <p style="text-align: left;">- He lacks confidence and avoids trying new things, or does not have the ability to face simple daily challenges.</p>
       <p style="text-align: left;">- He has difficulty concentrating.</p>
       <p style="text-align: left;">- He has problems sleeping or eating. He feels tantrums.</p>
       <p style="text-align: left;">- Has a lot of negative thoughts, or keeps thinking bad things are happening.</p>
       <p style="text-align: left;">- Avoids daily activities (such as seeing friends, going out in public, or going to school).</p>

    </div>
     <div class="container-xl py-5">
         <h3 class="mb-3">When should you see a doctor:</h3>
  <p style="text-align: left;">If the child’s anxiety is severe and persistent and interferes with his daily life.</p>
     </div>
        <div class="container-xl py-5">
            <h3 class="mb-3"> Treatment:</h3>
            <p style="text-align: left;">The type of treatment provided depends on the child’s age and the cause of his anxiety. It can help the child understand what makes him anxious, and allow him to work on overcoming the situation, in addition to: Cognitive behavioral therapy:
            </p>
              <p style="text-align: left;">- which is a talk therapy that can help the child manage his anxiety, by changing the way he thinks and behaves</p>
                          <p style="text-align: left;"> - Anxiety medications may be prescribed for a child by a doctor if their anxiety is severe or does not improve with talk therapies.
                              </p>

        </div>
        <div class="container-xl py-5">
            <h3 class="mb-3">Prevention:</h3>
            <p style="text-align: left;">Some children are more likely to develop anxiety when they experience trauma or stress, are abused, are bullied by other children, or when their parents suffer from anxiety or depression, although these factors seem to increase the risk of developing anxiety. Or depression, but knowing it alone helps in prevention and reduces the child’s chance of being exposed to anxiety.

            </p>

        </div>
        <div class="container-xl py-5">
            <h3 class="mb-3">Tips for parents when a child has anxiety:</h3>
            <p style="text-align: left;">It is important to talk to the child about his anxiety or fears, reassure him, and show that you understand how he feels, if the child is old enough; Explaining anxiety and its physical effects may help him and have a positive impact on him, and it is important for parents to help the child find solutions to overcome and overcome his anxiety, for example if your child is anxious about going to sleep; It is normal to want to tell him not to go, however this may mean that the child feels that his anxiety will prevent him from doing things, so it is best to recognize his anxiety and suggest solutions to help him so that he can go to sleep.

            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="container-xl py-5">
            <h4 class="mb-3">One way to relieve anxiety in children is:</h4>
            <p style="text-align: left;">  </p>
                        <p style="text-align: left;">- to help the child recognize the signs of anxiety. </p>
                        <p style="text-align: left;">- Encourage the child to manage his anxiety and seek help when he needs it. </p>
                        <p style="text-align: left;">  </p>
            <p style="text-align: left;">- Children of all ages find routine reassuring; So try to stick to your normal daily routine wherever possible.  </p>
            <p style="text-align: left;">- If a child is anxious due to traumatic events (such as trauma or separation), looking for books or movies that help him understand his feelings may be an appropriate solution  </p>
            <p style="text-align: left;">- If you know a change is coming (eg moving to a new home) prepare the child by talking to him or her about the upcoming change and its reasons.   </p>
            <p style="text-align: left;">- Try not to be overly protective or anxious about him. Practice simple relaxation techniques with your child (such as: taking 3 slow, deep breaths, or inhaling for a count of 3 and then exhaling for a count of 3).  </p>
            <p style="text-align: left;">- Distraction can be helpful for young children, for example if a child is anxious about going to nursery, play games all the way to nursery.  </p>


        </div>
        
